    </node>
    <node id="Binary Preference Objectives">
      <data key="d0">Binary Preference Objectives</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Binary preference objectives are used in pairwise ranking models to evaluate the relative quality of explanations.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-a42210fb81e37b65a494b714686acf98</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1777541275</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="AdapTime">
      <data key="d0">AdapTime</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">AdapTime involves three temporal reasoning actions: reformulate, rewrite, and review, to address different types of temporal questions.&lt;SEP&gt;AdapTime is an adaptive temporal reasoning method that enhances the temporal reasoning capabilities of large language models.&lt;SEP&gt;AdapTime integrates seamlessly with state-of-the-art large language models to enhance their temporal reasoning capabilities.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-a92919218c93fbc995ef28388a45a264</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1777541330</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Temporal Reasoning">
      <data key="d0">Temporal Reasoning</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Temporal reasoning involves understanding and manipulating time-related information in language models.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-a92919218c93fbc995ef28388a45a264</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1777541333</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="LLM Planner">
      <data key="d0">LLM Planner</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">The LLM planner is a component of AdapTime that guides the reasoning process by dynamically executing reasoning steps based on the input context.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-a92919218c93fbc995ef28388a45a264</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1777541337</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Temporal Questions">
      <data key="d0">Temporal Questions</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Temporal questions require distinct reasoning strategies, which AdapTime addresses through its adaptive approach.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-a92919218c93fbc995ef28388a45a264</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1777541337</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Temporal Reasoning Actions">
      <data key="d0">Temporal Reasoning Actions</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Temporal reasoning actions are the steps involved in AdapTime, including reformulate, rewrite, and review.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-a92919218c93fbc995ef28388a45a264</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1777541337</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="State-of-the-Art LLMs">
      <data key="d0">State-of-the-Art LLMs</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">State-of-the-art large language models are integrated with AdapTime to enhance their temporal reasoning capabilities.&lt;SEP&gt;State-of-the-art LLMs refers to the most advanced large language models.&lt;SEP&gt;State-of-the-art LLMs refers to the most advanced large language models.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-a92919218c93fbc995ef28388a45a264&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-306df29aef0348d52b474a51b48f7864</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1777541564</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Credal Concept Bottleneck Models">
      <data key="d0">Credal Concept Bottleneck Models</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Credal Concept Bottleneck Models are a type of model that predicts through human-interpretable concepts and decompose concept uncertainty by construction.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-186325b8d21aab395207850cb3577223</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1777541415</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Concept Bottleneck Models">
      <data key="d0">Concept Bottleneck Models</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Concept Bottleneck Models predict through human-interpretable concepts but typically output point concept probabilities that conflate epistemic uncertainty with aleatoric uncertainty.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-186325b8d21aab395207850cb3577223</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1777541415</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="CREDENCE">
      <data key="d0">CREDENCE</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">CREDENCE is a CBM framework that decomposes concept uncertainty by construction and represents each concept as a credal prediction.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-186325b8d21aab395207850cb3577223</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1777541417</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Epistemic Uncertainty">
      <data key="d0">Epistemic Uncertainty</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Epistemic uncertainty is reducible model underspecification that can be derived from disagreement across diverse concept heads.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-186325b8d21aab395207850cb3577223</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1777541422</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Aleatoric Uncertainty">
      <data key="d0">Aleatoric Uncertainty</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Aleatoric uncertainty is irreducible input ambiguity that can be estimated via a dedicated ambiguity output trained to match annotator disagreement when available.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-186325b8d21aab395207850cb3577223</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1777541422</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Credal Prediction">
      <data key="d0">Credal Prediction</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">A credal prediction is a probability interval that represents each concept in the CREDENCE framework.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-186325b8d21aab395207850cb3577223</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1777541424</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Concept Heads">
      <data key="d0">Concept Heads</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Concept heads are diverse models that contribute to the derivation of epistemic uncertainty in the CREDENCE framework.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-186325b8d21aab395207850cb3577223</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1777541426</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Annotator Disagreement">
      <data key="d0">Annotator Disagreement</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Annotator disagreement is used to train the dedicated ambiguity output in the CREDENCE framework and estimate aleatoric uncertainty.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-186325b8d21aab395207850cb3577223</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1777541428</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Prediction Errors">
      <data key="d0">Prediction Errors</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Prediction errors are positively associated with epistemic uncertainty in the CREDENCE framework.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-186325b8d21aab395207850cb3577223</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1777541430</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Error Correlation">
      <data key="d0">Error Correlation</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Error correlation is not sufficient to guide decisions in the CREDENCE framework, as it does not account for aleatoric uncertainty.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-186325b8d21aab395207850cb3577223</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1777541435</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Human-Interpretable Concepts">
      <data key="d0">Human-Interpretable Concepts</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Human-interpretable concepts are used by Concept Bottleneck Models to predict and decompose uncertainty.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-186325b8d21aab395207850cb3577223</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1777541439</data>
